Certainly! To change the size of an iframe using JavaScript, you can use the `style` property to modify its `width` and `height` CSS properties. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
  /* Style the iframe */
  #resizableIframe {
    width: 500px;
    height: 300px;
    border: none;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Your content before the iframe -->

<!-- Resizable iframe -->
<iframe id="resizableIframe" src="https://www.example.com"></iframe>

<!-- Your content after the iframe -->

<script>
  // Function to resize the iframe
  function resizeIframe(newWidth, newHeight) {
    var iframe = document.getElementById('resizableIframe');
    iframe.style.width = newWidth + 'px';
    iframe.style.height = newHeight + 'px';
  }

  // Example usage
  resizeIframe(800, 600); // Change the width to 800px and height to 600px
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this code:

1. The `#resizableIframe` selector in the `<style>` section sets the initial dimensions of the iframe.
2. The `resizeIframe` function uses JavaScript to change the width and height of the iframe.
3. The example usage of the `resizeIframe` function sets the width to 800 pixels and height to 600 pixels. You can call this function whenever you want to change the iframe's size.

Remember to replace the `src` attribute of the iframe with the URL of the content you want to display within the iframe. Adjust the initial dimensions and the example usage according to your requirements.

Communicating between an iframe and its parent document involves using the `postMessage` API in JavaScript. This allows you to send and receive messages securely. Here's how you can receive a message from an iframe:

Assuming you have an iframe like this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Your iframe content -->

<script>
  // Send a message to the parent document
  function sendMessageToParent() {
    var message = "Hello from the iframe!";
    parent.postMessage(message, '*'); // '*' allows communication with any origin
  }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

And a parent document like this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Your content before the iframe -->

<!-- Your iframe -->
<iframe id="myIframe" src="iframe.html"></iframe>

<!-- Your content after the iframe -->

<script>
  // Receive messages from the iframe
  window.addEventListener('message', function(event) {
    // Check the origin of the event
    if (event.origin !== "http://your-iframe-origin.com") {
      return;
    }

    // Handle the received message
    var receivedMessage = event.data;
    console.log("Received message from iframe:", receivedMessage);
  });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example:

1. The iframe contains a script that defines a `sendMessageToParent` function. When called, this function sends a message to the parent document using the `postMessage` method.

2. The parent document includes an iframe and a script that listens for the `message` event. When a message is received, the event's `data` property contains the message content. The script checks the `origin` of the event to ensure it's coming from a trusted source. Replace `"http://your-iframe-origin.com"` with the actual origin of your iframe.

3. Remember that the `postMessage` method uses the principle of cross-document messaging, which requires communication between documents from the same domain or with explicit trust through the `origin` check.

Always ensure that you handle received messages securely to prevent potential security vulnerabilities.
